      <div type="description" n="monument">
        <head>Description of Monument</head>
        <p>A <rs type="material" key="marmor">white marble</rs> <rs type="objectType">sarcophagus</rs> (<measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">0.30</measure> x <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="width">1.80</measure>) from which
part of the front and of the lower sides has been carefully removed.
It seems likely, but not certain, that this second inscription should
be associated with the cutting away of the front, although it is
difficult to envisage how the stone was then used - perhaps to support
a coffin?</p>
      </div>

      <div n="text" type="description">
        <head>Description of Text</head>
        <p>i:  lines 1-2 on the lower part of the
inscribed <term lang="la"><rs type="decoration">Tabella ansata</rs></term>, and in one line on the lower moulding.</p> <p>ii, published here, was cut along the upper edge of the back of the
sarcophagus.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="description" n="letters">
        <head>Description of Letters</head>
        <p>Standard forms, except for cursive <term>omega</term> and
<term>sigma</term>.</p>
      </div>

      <div type="description" n="date">
        <head>Date</head>
        <p><date notAfter="0333" exact="none" notBefore="0268">Late third/early fourth century</date> (titulature).</p>
      </div>

      <div n="text" lang="grc" type="edition">
        <head lang="en">Edition</head>
        <div type="textpart_section" n="i"><ab><lb n="0"/><gap extent="7" reason="lost" unit="character"/> <w lemma="ἀντίγραφον"><supplied reason="lost">ἀντίγ</supplied><lb n="1"/><supplied reason="lost">ρα</supplied>φον</w> <w lemma="ἀνατίθημι">ἀνετέθη</w> <w lemma="εἰς">εις</w>      <lb n="2"/><w lemma="βεκούλον">εις</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τὸ</w> <w lemma="χρεωφυλάκιον">χρεοφυλάκιον</w> <w lemma="ἐπί">ἐπὶ</w><lb n="3"/><w lemma="στεφανηφόρος"><supplied reason="lost">στεφα</supplied>νηφόρου</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τὸ</w> <num value="3">γ</num> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Ὑψικλῆς">Ὑψικλέους</name> <w lemma="ὁ">τοῦ</w> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Ἄδραστος">Ἀδράστου</name> <persName type="aphrodisian"><name reg="Νικότιμος">Νεικοτείμου</name> <name reg="Ἱέραξ">Ἱέρακος</name></persName></persName></persName> <w lemma="μείς">μηνὸς</w> <w lemma="Γορπιαῖος">Γορπιήου</w> <num value="9">θ</num>.</ab> 
      </div><div type="textpart_section" n="ii"><ab><lb n="1"/><w lemma="ἐνθάδε">ἐνθάδε</w> <w lemma="κεῖμαι">κεῖτε</w> <persName key="victorinus1" type="aphrodisian" full="yes"><name reg="Βικτωρεῖνος">Βικτωρεῖνος</name></persName> <w lemma="ἀπό">ἀπὸ</w> <rs type="official-secul" key="protector"><w lemma="πρωτήκτορ">πρωτηκτόρων</w></rs> <rs type="official-secul" key="praefvehic"><w lemma="ἔπαρχος">ἔπαρχος</w> <space dim="horizontal"/><lb n="2"/><w lemma="βεκούλον">βεκούλων</w>.</rs></ab> 
      </div></div>

      <div type="translation"><head>Translation</head><ab>i: [ . . . the copy ] was places in the Property archive when Hypsikles the son of Adrastos Neikotimos Hierax was stephanephoros for the third time, 9th day of the month Gorpieos.</ab><ab>ii: Here lies Biktorinos, former <term lang="la">protector</term>, <term lang="la">praefectus vehiculorum</term>.</ab></div><div type="commentary">
        <head>Commentary</head>
        <p>i:  a standard funerary text of the
second century; for the stephanephoros see Name index.</p><p>ii: See discussion at <xref type="eAla-text" n="IX.12">IX.12</xref>.</p>
      </div>

